# Enter the Switch

Imagine you are coding a vending machine. If the user presses A1, give chips. A2, give soda. A3, give candy... You could write an endless chain of `else if` statements.

Switch to the **`switch`** statement! It is designed specifically for cases where a single variable might have many different, exact values it could equal.

```javascript
// A cleaner alternative to 10 'else if' statements!
switch (buttonPressed) {
  // Code goes here
}
```

## Anatomy of a Switch

Inside a switch, we write **`cases`**. JavaScript looks at the variable, finds the matching case, and runs the code below it.

```javascript
let fruit = "apple";

switch (fruit) {
  case "apple":
    console.log("🍎");
    break;
  case "banana":
    console.log("🍌");
    break;
  default:
    console.log("❓");
}
```

The **`break;`** keyword is CRITICAL. It tells JavaScript to STOP running the switch block. If you forget `break`, the code will keep executing the next cases too! (This is called "falling through").

The **`default:`** keyword acts exactly like an `else` at the end of an if-chain. It catches anything that didn't match a case.

slides.codeSnippet:
let role = "admin";

switch (role) {
  case "admin":
    console.log("Full access granted.");
    break;
  case "editor":
    console.log("Editing tools unlocked.");
    break;
  case "user":
    console.log("Welcome to your dashboard.");
    break;
  default:
    console.log("Access Denied.");
}
